text:
tw: kavanaugh assault 
when i was probably 3 or 4, this little pine tree came up to about my height. a short time later, it was half eaten by a deer. for years it grew and blossomed, but it always had this one little spot where no green ever fully grew back. for christmas we would decorate it a little extra special and give it a little extra love. it became the most charming little pine tree on our property because of its navajo flaw, next to its tall green sisters. now i am 24, and this is how that little pine tree looks today. 
when a person experiences trauma - that experience, no matter how big or small, remains with them forever. it does not have to dictate their future, but it does not go away. the tree has never been and never will be held at fault for what happened to it, and the length of time that has passed from the event to now does not in any way lessen its validity, suggest it did not happen, or weaken its impact on its fully grown form. 
for christine ford, for the women who have recently come forward about multiple celebrities and people of power, and for all survivors of sexual assault no matter what gender: 
your story is heard. your experience matters. and we believe you. #istandwithchristineblaseyford

.

.
although sen. collins support would be a likely part of judge kavanaughâ€™s confirmation, the full and final vote in the senate isnâ€™t until tomorrow.
.
after she announced her support, sen. joe manchin, a democrat representing west virginia, announced he would also vote â€œyesâ€ to confirm judge kavanugh, crossing party lines.
.
link to speech is on our source page of this card on smarthernews.com - whether you agree with her decision or not, itâ€™s worth a read this weekend.

text: sixteen miles this morning, boom! ğŸ‘ŠğŸ» i started running nearly 20 years ago (omg what) at a time when i felt a little directionless, powerless, insecure, down. i saw the ironman on tv, and was so amazed by what these average seeming people could achieve with just their own bodies. i envied their direction, that they got to get up in the morning with a goal, a plan, something to aim for. and that they got to go to bed at night knowing that they achieved something... or at least that they tried their best. i started running the next day because i wanted that feeling. and honestly it's what keeps me running today. i run because it reminds me that i am powerful. that i can change my environment, that i can change myself, that i can move forward in space--sometimes for very long distances--using just my own physical and internal strength. that i am capable of withstanding much more than i think. that when i think i'm finished, it's over, i'm defeated... i never really am. this past week, and especially today, has been hard on many of us on many levels (ladies i'm looking at you). many of us--myself included--are feeling upset, angry, defeated down. i would encourage you to do something today that makes you feel powerful. remind yourself that you are capable of creating change and withstanding more than you think. that you are never really defeated, never really silenced, unless you allow yourself to be. then take that feeling of internal strength and power, and keep fighting. ğŸ’ªğŸ»ğŸ’¥ğŸ‘ŠğŸ»ğŸ”¥

.

text:
"do good, live in the most positive and joyful way possible every day." - roy t. bennett,Â the light in the heart

amen. i just finished an uplifting tweet chat organized by the talented @elsamariedsilva, discussing the issue of #childsexualabuse and my book "survivors: breaking the silence on child sexual abuse". it was incredible talking to other women warriors working in the same field, from as far away as india and pakistan. this here in the picture next to me is the lovely @okkyardya, a documentary photographer. we both did workshops together, at her invitation, in the indonesian province of east nusa tenggara in august. i wrote a piece on the human trafficking situation in indonesia, focusing on that province, to which okky contributed her amazing pictures. trigger warning: a couple of the photos are hard to look at. please head over to the link in my bio to read the blog post. what are you up to this wednesday? #projectbeauty #travel #traveling #indonesia #nusatenggaratimur #unveilhumantrafficking #girl #girls

text:
as long as black women have been brought to this country we have not been equals with our white counter parts as sojourner truth so eloquently illustrates in her speech ain't i a woman. feminism is not the black woman's fight, because black women have always worked outside of the home cleaning the white woman's home, cooking the white woman's food and caring for the white woman's chil'ren. black women have always been subjected to sexual harassment and rape and the white man took oir children and made them his house slave and uses their lighter skin tone to drive division between the slaves, fostering jealously by giving the "house slaves" a perceived advantage. 
it was a white woman who lied about sexual harassment and got the innocent, young emmitt till killed and his murderers were acquitted. 
at the center of the feminist movement is not right to work, it's not equal pay for equal work or sexual harassment, the core of feminism is roe v. wade. feminists don't want to lose the right to abort there babies, well not their babies, but our, black babies. don't believe me? research the founder, margaret sanger or just think about the kind of neighborhoods where you normally see planned parenthood facilities. 
now, there is actually a campaign geared towards black woman the abortion is "self care". this is a lie! not only does abortion kill the next generation of black children, it kills off subsequent generations, it comes with major health risks for women both physical and psychological. 
i stopped voting for a few reasons, one was the 2000 election, it was apparent to me at that tome the presidency has more to do with who your father is than how many votes you get, two i got tired of having to choose between the "lesser of two evils anf three, democrats don't care about black people. democrats are in favor of wellfare, because it keeps black people under their control and keeps the black family down. thank god i saw the light that abortion is wrong no matter the circumstances. yes, rape is wrong, but so is murder and two wrongs don't make a right.
#metoo #feminism #politics #democrat #republican #maga #conservative #liberal #abortion #plannedparenthood #prolife

text: a year and half ago, my self worth and almost everything i had worked my whole life to become, was taken from me. today i am incredibly ecstatic to feel like i'm meeting myself for the first time again. remembering fondly who i was before everything happened but finally happily welcoming this new version of myself who worked very hard to come back to me after hiding for a while. i think it's okay to do that. i've always loved change passionately. it keeps things interesting but having to relearn how to love yourself and your story in a very different way was terrifying. like looking in a mirror and seeing someone else, scary. i thought i'd never be me again, honestly. but i am and i'm new and i'm accepting and i'm ready for all the new things, people, and experiences life has to offer me. #openingupagain #metoo #selflove #welcomehome

text: tw: sa during my freshman year of college, a fellow student assaulted me. i was 17, drunk, in a freshman dorm. this guy had been hitting on me awhile and i was not interested. i was aware he wasnâ€™t really taking no for an answer. we were sitting in a room with a group of people when his friends all got up and left the two of us there abruptly. it felt coordinated. i was sitting on the floor and he crawled on top of me. i could hear people laughing outside the door. i repeated no over and over. i really thought he was going to rape me. i pushed him off and ran out of the room. the other people there were laughing about the encounter. the laughter - â€œthe uproarious laughterâ€ - is something you never forget. neither is the loss of a sense of safety in the world, especially after an attack that was clearly coordinated by a group of people. i never again drank carelessly. if you asked this person about the incident, he wouldnâ€™t remember it. it wasnâ€™t significant to him. i know the dorm it was in and the general time of year, but not the exact room or date. i am 100% certain about who the person is. i am also certain that if he were nominated to the supreme court someday, millions of people would not hesitate to support him or to discredit me. this is not a unique experience. this is womanhood. this week was the first time i told anyone about this. believe women. believe survivors. this is a disgrace. #metoo

text:
looking back at world history, it seems that things often need to hit rock bottom before they get better. and truthfully, itâ€™s appalling to even think about what rock bottom is going to be like. i feel angry and hopeless and dumbfounded that we as a country apparently still have so much farther to go. i know many women who feel like they are about to break. i do, too.
â€¢
it hurts. but yesterday, in the company of these two precious humans, my good friendâ€™s young daughters, i was reminded of something. i may be losing hope that i will be a part of a truly equal society in my lifetime. but i hope to god that these two girls will. and i have a responsibility to them, and all the other little girls in this country, to keep trying. to keep taking baby steps, to keep persisting amid a culture that systematically oppresses, disrespects, silences, undermines, and ignores women. to continue to do what i can on a daily basis to support, encourage, believe, comfort, and empower the strong, brave, and worthy women and girls in my life. to have faith that we will continue to move forward, no matter how slowly, because we as a gender have been through thousands of years of trauma and abuse and shaming and we ğŸ‘are ğŸ‘stillğŸ‘ here ğŸ‘
â€¢
to the amazing women i know: you are my heroes. i admire and respect your kindness, resilience, empathy, courage and power in the face of all the attempted indignities that are so commonplace, they feel like an unavoidable part of life. iâ€™m honored to know you and stand beside you. and if you feel as sad and angry as i do right now, i hear you and iâ€™m with you. you are not alone. 
#turnrageintochange #ibelieveher #believesurvivors #vote #blackfridays #metoo #womenempowerment #women #mayangelou #womensupportwomen #feminism

text:
day 5 of 30. moments of gratitude. wow. they days pass fast when your tracking them.  i guess thatâ€™s the things....days pass....which turns into weeks...then months...and sometimes years of gone by before you wake up and realize your really not as well as you thought. .
today i am reluctantly grateful for modern medicine. after a year of trying to deal with the demons naturally, thousands of dollars in supplements, oils and doctors....here i am...back to these stupid pink little pills.
.
i worked so hard to get off these damn things last year....learning what they were doing to my body...i just wanted to feel â€œmyselfâ€ again....to feel anything....so i stopped taking them.  but sometimes....ptsd is such an unpredictable beast....those feelings are too much to handle!  and right now....no matter how much i hate it...i need to be able to function...more than i need to be healing â€œau naturalâ€! .
.
so...my mind has calmed...the crazy has subsided....it may be artificial ...but for the moment, i feel okay. .
.
and for that i am grateful. .
.
.

text:
day 278: "as women, we can lose our dignity and any sense of safety or feelings of rights to public space that we might have- all on someone else's whim. this is how we come to accept harsh fact of violability. we bite our tongues, sometimes until they bleed." i anxiously await the day when my generation and future generations take control of our government and right the wrongs that the older generations have made. the times are changing and our government needs to adapt to those changes.

there is never a good time to come forward about sexual assault experiences. there is never a good time, because there shouldn't even be the experience. the double standard needs to stop. women have to start being believed.

text:
huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.
.
#nobelprize #endrapeinwar #nadiamurad #metoo

from â€œmen explain things to meâ€ by rebecca solnit.
our problem is a systemic culture that starts with disregard and disdain for women, especially as we age - we, who choose to give birth to all human beings - and then continues with silencing, and violence. #drblaseyford took a bullet to try and upend this normalcy, like @anitahillofficial did.Â Â both heroes.Â Â listening to these old rep senators denounce her, and vote in this ill-tempered, belligerent, would be rapist (what was he trying to do, dance with her, once he could shut her up and take her clothes off?)Â that spittling, throaty, constant beer-refraining â€œi like beer, do you like beer?â€ douchebag, is what you get when the @realdonaldtrump is an admitted sexual predator and is sitting in the highest office, protected by republican senators like the bullshit hr departments and pr people that protected the likes of weinstein to moonves, all the way down.Â Â there is no bar too low for the republicans (and manchin) - they hide behind trumpâ€™s populist fury like a bunch of pussies hiding behind a bully on the school playground.Â Â theyâ€™ve never had such a pure mission now, pushing back on #metoo and @timesup.Â Â everyone knows that women are continually sexually attacked, and then attacked again as victims, so we are not seeing anything new here.Â Â of the men who have been yanked from their throne due to sexual assault, who has come back and denied it, put up a fight?Â Â theyâ€™ve all just climbed down from their big powerful swivel chairs and slunk into their mansions and sat in their man lairs, fingering their trophies and bumping into walls with their anger, wondering not, how did i get here? but how can i get back to the terrificness of where i was?Â Â zero self-reflection, no real apologies, just fury.Â Â which is really such a depressing circle jerk of misplaced anger.Â Â unless we vote these fuckers out.Â Â shame on all of you @sensucollins @senmitchmcconnell @joesenatorf782 @lindseygrahamsc et al.Â Â to have this sham of a biased, federalist-groomed, punch drunk, beer swilling frat boy on #scotus who will vote to overturn #roevwade equally out of misplaced spite, partisan politics, & an utter disregard for women? text:
me too. you too. us too.

sadness and anger is just festering inside me. our country is in such turmoil. my stomach turns daily. 
a year since the #metoomovement began and what have we accomplished? has there been any progress? will there ever be? 
as a woman and a single parent to a young boy, i feel lost and completely unsupported by the country i call home. it's scary. 
i suppose we have much purging to do before the real healing begins. i have to believe that's where we are heading. 
#metoo #believeus #drford #notmypresident

text:
itâ€™s #fridayintroductions for #followfriday time!â €
â €
my personality is best understood by the fact that i was born on #october 16, 1981 at 4:58pmâ€”that is, a friday in mid-october with most adults leaving work for the weekend. #bestmonth iâ€™m a 7w8 & enfp except really i am a true ambivert.â €
â €
i have survived extreme trauma. sexual assault by my father began at 2 *days* old. my story is complex, speaking & believed, speaking & silenced, speaking & called a liar. â €
â €
i cannot count how many men assaulted me in my youth. i was also physically & emotionally abused, & my home was rife with poverty & very unsafe.â €
â €
i thought i knew the worst & got out; at 35 i found out i remember the basics & the worst memories are blocked. this is one of multiple survival methods i employed to get out.â €
â €
i am fat. a size 22/24. my body has lived in extreme trauma mode for 30+ years; i only found out that my mind has blocked this in the last two. my body is wracked with chronic illness & refuses to lose weight. and yes, i have tried everything.â €
â €
i am an #exvangelical. at 16 i was drawn to fundamentalism. i was desperate for love & purity culture was a giant band-aid to blanket my fear of sexual attention. at 35 i left. iâ€™m 90% atheist, 10% uncertain. sometimes that flips.â €
â €
i have an amazing husband & two kids on the autism spectrum, a delightful 2yo, & a medically fragile baby.â €
â €
my core value is to be motivated by love, not fear. in everythingâ€”relationships, inner thoughts, parenting, eating, exercise, skin care, money planning, self care, intersectional feminism, politics, inclusion, writing, holding space, everything. â €
â €
except driving. really trying to be motivated by love while driving.â €
â €
iâ€™m always ğŸ’¯ with raw vulnerability. i believe story changes us, moves us from apathy & fear to empathy & love. â €
â €
i am alive. after a horrific childhood & free from oppressive religion. i have this one fucking life & i am making it what i want before itâ€™s gone. love fuels my freedom fire. ğŸ”¥â €
â €
welcome. i hope you stay. ğŸ’™

emergency protest following the senate vote of brett kavanaugh to the supreme court! we will gather in columbus, cleveland, cincinnati, and dayton tomorrow across the state of ohio at 12:00 p.m. link in bio or go to womenâ€™s march ohio on facebook for details!
.
.
.
.
this saturday, 10/6, the senate is expected to vote. we must show up in numbers too great to ignore & make sure they hear our demand to #believesurvivors and #cancelkavanaugh! 
dr. christine blasey ford testimony brought #metoo survivors together sharing stories however our lives remain on the line thanks to an unjust process. kavanaugh threatens our rights, our health, our justice system & more. millions watched live as dr. ford was unwavering in her testimony, while kavanaugh painted himself as a victim, though a belligerent and dishonest one. 
kavanaugh should have been forced to withdraw on behalf of his statement that presidents can ignore laws and his long record of consistently taking the side of corporations over their employees.  now he is close to being confirmed despite being accused of a perpetrator of sexual violence and lying under oath.

this is not just a moment but a movement to fight against kavanaugh and the trump administration.  we need to keep on pushing and moving against policies of misogyny and exploitation! #cancelkavanaugh!

text:
so many men fear the power of womenâ€™s bodies that, in a desperate bid to control the uncontrollable, they assume the role of tyrantâ€”while claiming to provide benevolent protection. how do i know women will ultimately win this centuries-long battle? because without us, men donâ€™t even exist.  below, todayâ€™s post from brilliant nyc photographer and filmmaker @nina_berman, an excellent reminder of how long women have been fighting for the same thing: our right to just be. ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
in 1977 as a teenager i volunteered at planned parenthood in nyc. i would go around to clinics and collect signatures from clients in opposition to the hyde amendment, named after illinois congressman henry hyde.  the amendment, passed in 1976, barred federal funds from paying for abortion (meaning poor women and girls were targeted) and was the first of many attempts to strip away the rights affirmed by roe v wade. since then iâ€™ve photographed dozens of scenes from clinic battle lines, to doctors who go to work in bullet proof vests. i feel sick that we have slipped so far back and men like brett kavanaugh, donald trump and mitch mcconnell are telling us what we can and canâ€™t do with our bodies.  itâ€™s gratifying to see the current generation standing up now and realizing nothing can be taken for granted. we are in the fight for our lives. here is a picture from 1989 when pro-choice demonstrators blocked streets and stormed the brooklyn bridge following the supreme court webster decision which allowed states the right to restrict abortion. â€”- photo Â©ï¸ nina berman

text:
susan collins just spent the last 50 minutes praising brett kavanagh and his judicial record. she talked about her "outrage that allegations of sexual assault could even make it into the confirmation process." she said that although she believes christine blasey ford was assaulted at some time, her allegations failed to meet a standard of proof and cannot prevent kavanagh from being appointed to the supreme court. she did not mention the other women who also accused kavanagh of different levels of sexual assault, and she didn't mention brett kavanagh's blatantly partisan behavior during his judiciary hearing. she then told the senate and the country that she will vote yes tomorrow to confirm brett kavanagh to the supreme court. it is now a done deal. tomorrow, accused sexual predator, brett kavanagh, will become the swing vote on the united states supreme court. make no mistake, the supplemental investigation into allegations of sexual assault against brett kavanagh, was a sham conducted for the sole purpose of making it look like they even considered allegations of sexual assault as a disqualifier for a lifetime appointment on the highest court in the land, which clearly they do not! jeff flake is voting yes and so are democratic senator joe manchin, and all the other supposed undecided senators with the exception of lisa murkowski, who voted no on the cloture vote today and is expected to vote no again tomorrow on the actual vote to confirm.

text:
#metoo

he was the brother of my roommateâ€™s girlfriend. i had dated him previously, but we were not together at the time. i was still in love with him, but he had told me he was not going to be with me. it crushed me. i drowned my feelings in vodka sodas, and blacked out. i woke up the next day in my bed alone, naked, with all points of entry on my body raw and painful. i looked at my phone and saw a series of agressive texts that went unanswered by me. "why are you passed out?" "so you're gonna get drunk and not even f*** me?" "this is bullsh*t". i don't need to have recalled every single detail of what happened that night. i was blacked out, my abuser knew it, and took advantage of not only my inability to give consent, but my emotional state as well. i could have said yes, but i was not in a position to do so coherently. and i don't have to remember the events that occurred to know that i was physcially taken advantage of. you don't wake up in pain the day after being intimate with someone who cares about you. 
did this make you feel uncomfortable? good. i'm glad it did. 
you may have opinions on my #metoo experience. truthfully, i don't care, and i don't want to hear them. this is my experience, my perception, my truth. i want to share this to make speaking out more normal, and to try to help start creating a safe place and space for women, amongst other women and men who have our best interests at heart. i don't speak out politically much, but today has grown to be too much for me to keep silent. 
today, as the first friday of the #blackfridays movement, i wear black to stand in solidarity for victims of sexual abuse. i stand in solidarity for women of color, for immigrants, for children ripped from their families. i amÂ  scared for my daughter's future in this country. i don't know how to talk to her about any of this, and i tear up as i write this, because i have to find a way. we have to start talking about the uncomfortable if we want change. 
#turnrageintochange #blackfridays #onfridayswewearblack

text: the first time i was sexually assaulted, i was only a child. i felt scared, alone, and that i was to blame. i prayed to god to â€œtake the bad thing out of meâ€. the next time i was 13. it was by someone i knew. they were more popular than me, and i knew if i told anyone, iâ€™d just be called a slut because everyone in high school already called me a slut anyway. the last time i was 17. i was drunk at a party and it was a boy i hardly knew. i told him to stop and we were in a room full of other people passed out. i still wonder everyday if one of them was secretly awake listening to what happened to me. this week has been one of the hardest of my life. the kavanaugh hearings are heartbreaking for a multitude of reasons. regardless of if you believe he assaulted those who have come forward, the blatant disrespect he (and others, including trump) has shown toward them speaks volumes. i have also had to walk around my campus everyday feeing silenced and deeply unsettled by the fact that individuals truly believe women should have the right to control their own bodies taken away, not realizing the trauma some of us have endured. today, may we recognize the strength of the women around us. may we never forget how far we have come, but never underestimate how far we have to go. #metoo #ibelieveher #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #iamtheprochoicegeneration

text:
on fridays i wear black because what's happening in this world is bullshit! i am mad. i'm tired of being quiet and complacent. ğŸ–¤
when a woman...a survivor tells her story believe her! we are told that our stories are wrong. that what happens to us is our fault and when something does happens we should keep it to ourselves (because if we don't we will be victim shamed). we are taught to be quiet and smile through the pain. well... i'm tired of smiling and staying quiet. ğŸ–¤
i was sexually assaulted by multiple men. a guy friend at a college party when we had too much to drink, by a random guy i met at the mall in high school, by a boyfriend who refused to take no for an answer (we were in a committed relationship and if i didn't want him to leave me i better do what he wanted to do... it didn't matter if i said no, if i said i didn't want to - he manipulated me into doing what he wanted me to do- because he know i was terrified that he would leave me- and in my mind at that time it was better to be sexually assaulted then to be alone). ğŸ–¤ 
my story is not much different from the millions of other women who have been sexually assaulted. they live with the shame, the pain and the memories. they push them away and out of their mind. they try with every ounce of their being to forget what happened - but i know no matter how hard i try. it will haunt me for my entire life. ğŸ–¤
 i will not be silent today even though itâ€™s hard to press share.... anyone who know me knows my anxiety gets in the way when it comes to speaking my mind. im going to be brave and do this anyway. i will keep sharing my story in hopes another woman hears it. so she knows she is not alone. so if this happens to her she is able to come forward and speak to someone about it. so she doesn't have to spend 15+ years of her life trying to pretend everything is ok. #ibelieveher #ibelieveyoutoo #believesurvivors #itsnotyourfault #metoo

text: one year ago today, the harvey weinstein scandal was released to the public in a groundbreaking @nytimes article. similar allegations against other powerful men soon followed. women have been harassed in the workplace since workplaces were invented, and started feeling more comfortable to start speaking about their own experiences, starting the #metoo movement. a large group of powerful women created the @timesupnow fund for victims of workplace sexual harassment. charlie rose lost his job. matt lauer was fired from the today show. weinstein was indicted. bill cosby was sent to prison. this is proof that no matter how powerful a man may be, he will still be held accountable for his actions. now, more than ever, we need to believe survivors. we can #cancelkavanaugh.

text:
post 4: ever thought what a sexually harassed person goes through mentally? they feel opened up just like this. if you have been wrongly touched, sexually har
rassed or abused, you may have experienced some level of depression or anxiety and takes you back to the moment when the incident took place.

after a session with my first client who was diagnosed with ptsd, i went to the washroom and cried. i felt this was not what i signed up for. i felt i'm not strong enough to help someone who has experienced sexual harasment. it's only with time, i believed in myself and my clients as well.

something i tell most clients - it's not impossible to live a healthy life after what happened. small steps to follow: what has proven to help is talking about this with either someone you confide in or a mental health professional. you can start with talking to a trusted person and eventually seek help from a psychologist who can help create coping mechanisms that help deal with the trauma caused. if there are triggers you deal with on a daily basis, it is very important to be aware of and observe what happens to you emotionally and physically.

remember, you're not a victim but a survivor and you're made up of so much more than that unforgettable and unfortunate incident. if you are a survivor and empathise with what's being said, feel free to share what worked for you and what didn't. it might just help another survivor.

#mentalhealthawareness #worldmentalhealthday #sexualharassment #spreadingandsharing #metoo

text:
nadia murad is a human rights activist from iraq. she was one of an estimated 3,000 girls and women from the yazidi minority who were victims of rape and other abuses by the terror group isis when it overran key cities in the country in 2014.

in testimony to the united states congress in june 2016, murad detailed how she and thousands of other yazidi women and girls enslaved and raped by their isis captors. she recounted how six of her brothers and her mother were executed by isis in a single day.
murad eventually escaped to mosul where a muslim family helped her obtain fake islamic identification that enabled her to escape isis territory.

in 2016, at the age of just 23, she was named the unâ€™s first goodwill ambassador for the dignity of survivors of human trafficking, the nobel committee said.
#nobelpeaceprize2018 
#metoo 
#nadiamurad .

text_retweet:
#repost @thediyphilosopher
a week ago, i joined #cancelkavanaugh protests at the supreme court, and it's been an emotional roller coaster since. it's easy to feel discouraged, but i want to keep sharing what's happening behind the scenes of the media circus. unless you actively pay attention, or hear about celebrities getting arrested, you might not know that hundreds of grassroots activists have shown up every. damn day since this nomination process started. i shared two posts earlier this week about my experience with this last friday. today i continue the story: how it ended that day, and why i'm inspired to show up more. surrounded by police, we met up next to the giant black sculpture in the hart atrium. hundreds of people milled about in near-silence. raising your voice or sitting on the floor is prohibited unless you're willing to risk arrest. we gathered with women who drove cross-country overnight to face their representatives. female + non-binary assault survivors. women of color. people with wheelchairs, service dogs, translators. lgbtq allies. men. mothers with children in tow. we waited and listened as tension built. then, above us, protestors on the balconies unfurled @womensmarch banners and started chanting. the crowd erupted, fists raised in response, chanting back. in minutes, police started making arrests. quickly, we split up and headed to key senate offices. my group flooded the office of @sensusancollins to sit in and share our stories with her staff. the room was in tears hearing how assault victims' lives have been destroyed, in part because society keeps glossing over the terrible behavior of men, putting them in charge of shit, and then wondering why the fuck things are like this. we left her office and stood chanting in the hallway, waiting to be arrested if necessary, when we heard that the investigation would move forward. and for a moment, we felt victorious. but we need to do more. when you think you don't have time to take action, remember the people who show up every day. when you feel too scared to call a politician, think of those who stand up in person for you. when you don't know what to do something instead of nothing. vote.

have you been thinking about false accusations lately? if so, here are some important facts:

1. since 1989 (when us records on this topic began) there are only 319 cases where men convicted of sexual assault were exonerated because it turned out they were falsely accused.
2. false rape accusations are incredibly rare. there are three decent studies on this topic (see below) - estimates range from 2.1% to 7.1% of reports being false. for this graphic, i took the midpoint then followed the statistics through to make an estimate about whether individuals faced criminal consequences as a result of these allegations.
3. what planet are you on if you think that itâ€™s common for people to make this shit up? #believesurvivors

sources: department of justice, office of justice programs, bureau of justice statistics, national crime victimization survey, 2010-2014 (2015); national incident-based reporting system, 2012-2014 (2015); felony defendants in large urban counties, 2009 (2013). heenan, m., & murray, s. (2006). study of reported rapes in victoria 2000-2003: summary research report. retrieved from the state of victoria (australia), department of human services: lonsway, k. a., archambault, j., & lisak, d. (2009). false reports: moving beyond the issue to successfully investigate and prosecute non-stranger sexual assault. the voice, 3(1), 1-11. national registry of exonerations

text: over the last two weeks i have had so many people say â€œif it was you, you would remember more than she claims to rememberâ€. these comments, mostly made by men, falsely assume that it hasnâ€™t happened to me. so now itâ€™s my turn. when i was 5/6 my neighbors son who was much older than me would touch me and make me touch him. he would tell me that i wasnâ€™t allowed to leave the room or that we couldnâ€™t do what i wanted to do until i cooperated with him. i couldnâ€™t tell you what year for sure, i couldnâ€™t tell you exactly how old i was. i couldnâ€™t tell you how many times it happened because it happened multiple times. i was afraid to speak up because i was worried that my dad would be mad at me, that he would think it was my fault because i was his little girl and i let it happen. i was so young, but these were the thoughts in my head. as i grew up i realized that it wasnâ€™t my fault and that i was a victim of sexual assault. i didnâ€™t talk to anyone about it, most of my family doesnâ€™t know and i havenâ€™t talked to friends about it. this fucked me up. i canâ€™t sleep in a house alone. i didnâ€™t sleep in my own bed until 7th grade because i was afraid of being alone. i had to learn to go to sleep to the tv because at least the sound made it seem like someone was with me. there is no evidence that this happened and at the end of the day it would come down to his word against mine. i didnâ€™t tell anyone, and the way that people have talked to me about the â€œwhat ifâ€ it was me has been more difficult than any of them could ever understand. watching the president of the united states openly mock a women for sharing her story makes me cry at night. typing this out doesnâ€™t feel real. #metoo #believesurvivors

text:
so much trauma has been awakened in us collectivelyâ€”new memories, old memories, and the ancient ones that have been carried in our cells. so much to feel and yet such a gift and a medicine to have it here, on the surface, where we can embrace it as we never did before.
.
and we arenâ€™t just revisiting our trauma, we are walking through reporting it, prosecuting it, speaking our story and naming our perpetrator. i was there with dr. ford, living out the day in court i never had. many of us were and it is empowering us, healing us.
.
it is shedding light on the subtle shades of sexual violence, inspiring #whyididntreport to raise their voices and their rights. it is dislodging the shame that once gripped our throats and pinned our power to the headboard of a wounded patriarchy. and it is pushing all of usâ€”men and womenâ€”to own our part in perpetuating that shame and those wounds. it is our common inheritance after all, to which our complacency and our blame has held us indentured. but #nomore
.
thatâ€™s big medicine and thereâ€™s more brewing. and, it will likely come with challenges.
.
already, our stale paradigm has made its disregard clear with a half-hearted investigation and a whole-hearted mocking from our president. more triggers to the many who also had to swallow a he said-she said stalemate and the shaming inquisition that chased it.
.
â€œitâ€™s not worth prosecutingâ€, i was told, after learning that the detective had â€œlostâ€ all the evidenceâ€”evidence plucked, swabbed, and stripped from my shaking body. gone. and with it, my credibility. even before that, small town eyes had turned toward my virtue. my grandmother suggested marriage while others questioned my virginity.
.
my story is one of many and though 25 years have passed, #notenough has changed. yesterdayâ€™s events energized me though. for i could feel hidden threads of complacency and blame unwinding within me. all the little ways in which i had coped with, resigned to, and even expected a world in which i was preyâ€”they unwound and opened into an undeniable call to action.
.
this is the medicine brewing and it is potent. listen for it, feel for it, and follow it. your revolution canâ€™t begin without you. ğŸ‘ŠğŸ»

the #metoo movement has come back into the light recently with the hashtag #whyididntreport. this has all come following the nomination of kavanaugh as the newest supreme court member. dr. christine blasey ford, a psychology professor from palo alto, accuses kavanaugh of sexual assault from their high school days. many were quick to dismiss her, and in return others began sharing their stories of why they didnâ€™t report what happened to them earlier under the hashtag #whyididntreport on twitter. more and more women are sharing their stories, and we believe them and stand with them. all of this continues to show that this abuse of women is way too prevalent in society and we hope that we can work together to change to create a better future.

text: when i was 16, i offered to tutor a male friend in math. i was a good student, he needed to get his grades up, so why not. we were in the public library, sitting at a regular table. and as i was going through the problems, he proceeded to take his hand and place on the inside of my thigh, creeping his way up. i said, "what are you doing?", he immediately let go, tried to explain himself and stumbled on his words. almost wondering how he read me being a nice person, as an okay to put his hands on me. my 16-year-old vulnerable, virgin, over-thinking mind started thinking, well i must have given off the wrong vibe. i must have been too nice, i shouldn't have offered to help, it was my fault. my bad. i am not 16 anymore. he was, and i assume still is - not a bad person. but like most men i know, entitled. entitled. i did nothing wrong, he did. he should have known better to put his hands on me. i grew up being taught, if it's not yours, don't touch it. i would feel selfish calling myself a victim of sexual abuse, this boy didn't cover my mouth and force himself on top of me. he didn't punch me or drug me. he didn't rape me. but every time i hear someone's #metoo story, that is the most seared experience i have in my head. aside from the many faces of men i'll never remember that have ever cat called me from their car, that casually rubbed their hand on my butt at nightclubs, or came up behind me crotch forward and expected me to dance with them. entitled. every single one of them. kavanaugh, trump, and all their lackeys. this is not a democrat vs republican matter. if it is to you, this is way over your head. this is about believing victims, and holding the perpetrators responsible for their actions. i have two sons. it's a huge responsibility. i hope to instill in them responsibility, kindness, and respecting humans, women included. women have been on this earth as long as men, and we have had to fight way harder to prove our worth and equality. to vote, to wear pants, to make the same amount of money for the same job. we carry humans. we birth humans! ** continued in comment section.

text:
what we have been witnessing over the last couple of weeks is a blatant display of white privilege.

kavanaugh's comments relied heavily on attending catholic school and how accomplished he was, citing his excellent grades and being captain of sports teams as if that is either proof that he was not guilty of doctor christine blasey ford's allegations, or enough reason for why they shouldn't matter.  it is painfully obvious to most that dr. ford has absolutely no motivation to invent her story and that kavanaugh's answers and behavior wreaked of guilt.
.
the outrage at the treatment of kavanaugh is a clear illustration of the good old boy's network at its best, dismissing the actions of kavanaugh as no big deal.
.
and it seems to be working. just as we arrive at the capitol building this morning to protest his confirmation, we receive word that the senators are keeping their eyes and ears shut and advance the confirmation to saturday for a final vote.
beyond sad!

text:
i'm a survivor of sexual assault.
i can't express enough to #votenoonkavanaugh !

thanks aclu of alaska for chance to travel and the opportunity to be part of #100akwomen . 
that being said let's not forget transwomen, non-confirming, non-binary, feminine folks are all #valid! i kept hearing "women" mostly referred towards cis-women and would like to clarify an open dialogue towards gender friendly language to include all folks who don't identify as cis. we're all part of this fight! all part of this march of human rights, validation and awareness on sexual assault surviors.

personal note> i had some issues with people using the correct pronouns, not accepted by few cis-females (who believed i shouldn't have been part of 100akwomen group) and usage of restrooms in dc. 
#alaskan#lgbtq #stopkavanaugh#metoo #trans#transgender#transisbeautiful#transmasculine#nonbinary#queer#lgtbq#webelieveallsurvivors#acknowledgeallgenders#allgendersarevalid#webelievesurvivors

text:
thank you, congress. thank you, america. thank you for making it abundantly irrefutably clear that women donâ€™t matter. that rape culture and toxic masculinity are the laws of the land, that my assaults and all the assaults of all the women of this country are somehow our fault, figments of our imagination, and just part and parcel of growing up girl. and though i feel compassion for the women who are deeply entrenched in internalized misogyny, your partisan votes are a betrayal to yourselves, to women everywhere and are ultimately a hate crime. my hope is that the collective devastation and outrage felt by not only women but the allies we have in the men and non-binary community who support basic human rights, who believe us, who march for us, who love and support us, who stand up for us, will serve as a catalyst to fight even harder, to show up en masse to vote, to march, to love, and to refuse to back down until our voices are not only heard, but listened to, validated, and ultimately break this cycle of systemic abuse and violation that we have suffered at the hands of this government for lifetimes. make no mistake, this revolution will be televised, we will love more, we will battle on, we will not be silenced, and we will not stand down. buckle up conservative america. we. are. coming. for. you. and. your. fucking. laws. 
#metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen #fucktrump  #stopkavanaugh #battleon 
#therevolutionwillbetelevised #revolution #riotgrrrl #lovemore #thetimeisnow #girlstothefront

huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.

in the last two weeks i had better conversations on #sextech #feminism #sexed #inclusivity #metoo #kink and #consent than in a loooooong time anywhere else in the world - and oh my, the orgasms ğŸ’˜

if you are the smartest person in the room, you are in the wrong room, they say. new york, you are the right room for me. i leave you hungry, raw and begging for more.

thank you so much @jeanettehepp
@_edditude_
and @muttisoyeah @johaennnsen and @womanizerglobal, @thevclubnyc
and @odotschool, @unboundbabes and @chacrubs and of course @melissaavitalepr
and @danielsaynt from @wearensfw

auf wiedersehen. soon ğŸ”¥

huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.
.

text: an awful lot has hit the fan for me in the last 200 days.  i went from the #peak of #success to the pit of depression.  the trigger was my success!!! instead of floating on air i felt like i was drowning!  i lost my motivation, desire, focus & drive.  i went through the motions of life but felt like i was dying!  my fatigue, pain amplified; my mind turned off,  i was like a zombie!  i  cut back on coffee to decrease my fatigue. i succeeded in mastering my coffee addiction but it didn't make me feel any better. my smoking was getting out of control so i quit. i am now almost 5 months nicotine free.  it has had benefits financially and physically, but it didn't make me feel any better. finally i went back to mental health because i was concerned regarding the level of my anxiety and the depth of my depression. during the anxiety group we did a session on guilt, shame and worry. in the session workbook, they give examples regarding what they're talking about and i found myself on those pages!! it took my breath away and it shook me to the core... because ...how could i not have remembered the things that i was thinking about?????? it was like i was reading a script for my life story... but...if you had asked me before day 800 about #metoo i would have told you that... apart  from the  lewd comments and awkward moments we have all experienced... i've never really experienced anything like that myself. i was wrong...so wrong!! the #resurfacing of these #memories has been almost #unbearable  today is day 1000 and for my own sanity...it is also day 1!  it has triggered danerously #unhealthy #copingbehaviors  #openmind #openwound  #bingeeating #bingeandpurge ğŸ–¤ğŸ–¤ğŸ–¤ğŸ’”ğŸ’”ğŸš¶â€â™€ï¸ğŸ‘£ğŸŒ #imcryingontheinside #confessions #mmj #thc #cbdoilÂ  #ms#hemochromatosis #chronicpainÂ  #chronicfatigue #depression #anxiety #distress #mentalhealthawareness #emotionalwellness  #spoonieÂ #spoonielife #workingonwellnessÂ  #willpowerismyname

text:
if i appear angry here, itâ€™s because i am. not at my audience but by our political events. when faced with our countryâ€™s rhetoric about survivors, especially women, first i was drained. now, iâ€™m back to being pissed off. back to the work i am honored to do. 
the last two week have been insanely exhausting listening to a bunch of men in dc go on about something they donâ€™t understand and clearly have no desire to. if i look angry, it is because i am. but from that anger comes passion. for research. for education. for change. 
thanks for nothing, gop. actually, thanks for the motivation. the motivation to make better men than you. to continue changing how we treat survivors and talk about sexual violence. 
we deserve better than this. and we will make it a reality. 
#survivor #metoo #speaker

.

.

.

text:
you guys,  i know you speak this in such a good hearted way, but i canâ€™t. â€”
i canâ€™t  because even though these statements are made to bring peace, it makes me feel like i need to remain silent, because iâ€™m not over it then. â€”
you need to know that just because people are having these conversations, and they are coming forward with their own stories doesnâ€™t mean that they are not over their experiences. i have moved on from my assault, i have lived a pretty amazing life, one that i know god blessed me with. i have found the person i was meant to be, i have found the person i was meant to be with, and created a life that was meant to be in this world. â€”
under no circumstances does me having an â€œemotional reactionâ€ to things said to me, to what is being said in our media, and what is going on in our nation mean that i havenâ€™t moved on. having an emotional reaction to things is normal, it is so so normal. it doesnâ€™t mean that i donâ€™t have â€œtrue powerâ€ because i would rather use the voice that i was given to speak up rather then remain silent. i promise it doesnâ€™t mean that i donâ€™t observe things, and i form my own opinions that way. it doesnâ€™t mean that i wear a badge with my truth everywhere i go, or in every aspect of my life. i can promise you that i have taken so many breaths, and to let things pass by, but i canâ€™t, i just canâ€™t right now. â€”
know that when people come forward to speak their truth they arenâ€™t doing it for encouragement, they are doing it to encourage. to encourage others to come forward, to encourage a change in our culture, to let people know these hard conversations are okay to have. â€”
i am speaking this out of love you guys, i am speaking this because it needs to be said. i am speaking because if i can even help one person come forward, or one person to look at things from a different view, or work with a greater group to promote change, it will be worth it for me. â€”
so no, my true power isnâ€™t sitting back, observing and letting things pass all the time. it is standing up and using my voice and experience when i can, even if it is hard because maybe just 1 single person needs to hear it.

"do you not see how necessary a world of pains and troubles is to school an intelligence and make it a soul?â€
. â€“ john keats (ascendant conjunct chiron).
.
oh, our achey breaky hearts! chiron, the wounded healer, recently returned to pisces for one last mission, very much setting the tone for venus retrograde in scorpio. our connection, as a collective, to sourceâ€”to the great cosmic onenessâ€”has been thrown out of balance. chironâ€™s healing work is centered on integration: traumaâ€™s sharps are never isolated. as one plunges deeper, the archipelago reveals the far-flung sweep of its greater mountain range. in pisces, chiron can see underwater, glowing his angler-fish lantern at depths even the sun wonâ€™t reach. iâ€™ll be posting at length on venus retrograde soon, but chironâ€™s return to the deep waters of the fish will be hugely influential, setting the tone for aphroditeâ€™s reverse botticelli.
.

.
chironâ€™s short teaser of aries has ended, and the wounded healer has returned to redress piscean wounds that have been festering in the collective in #thesetryingtimes
.

text:
â€˜medusa, for your pride this has been done.  your face is now so terrible to behold that the mere sight of it will turn a man to stone,â€ proclaimed the goddess, â€œeven you, medusa, should you seek your reflection, shall turn to rock the instant you see your face.â€
and with that, athena sent medusa with her hair of snakes to live with the blind monsters -- the gorgon sisters -- at the ends of the earth, so that no innocents would be accidentally turned to stone at the sight of her.â€™ - an excerpt from a book meant for children.

and perhaps this is why as women we grow up in a system where we take the abuses and keep quiet about the men who betrayed our trust. this is also why we distrust other women. remember, it was athena who cursed medusa because the latter was raped in her temple. 
this is what patriarchy has done to us. it has made us judge the other woman. and maybe we have just started to speak about it. we have held the anguish for so long reading fairy tales about unhappy girls like cinderella whose only chance at happiness lies in the fact that the prince rescues her. we have pitched women against women. the stepsisters and the stepmother in cinderellaâ€™s case are the ones who are against her. 
i sometimes wonder if the prince groped her while they danced. or if he betrayed her after she went with him. 
and did cinderella fight back? we donâ€™t know. this is not an easy battle. and those who have abused us are not â€œinnocentsâ€.
and perhaps we should stop reading fairy tales. we donâ€™t need a prince to rouse us from our eternal sleep. we need only ourselves. 
and i hope we also stand up and speak about emotional abuse and the trauma we suffer along with the sexual abuse that paralyses is for life and may we all be blessed with the gaze of medusa to turn men into stone.

.

text: invite the light in â˜€ï¸ i have a surya (sun) mandala tattooed on my right inner elbow. why? because the light always outshines the dark. the sun rises every morning, no matter how shitty the night before may have been, it still rises. no matter what stress we have in our lives we can always remember, each day is created anew. nothing changes that. nothing. ever. even on days that are cloudy, the sun is still there. just like our inner bliss (ananda). i like to think of it like "this little light of mine, i'm gonna let it shine" ğŸ¶ even though the light may sometimes be dim and harder to see, it's always there. it's our job to ignite our own fire, the light within, our true bliss. nobody, no substance, no herb, nothing can do this work for you. there may be people that help you navigate your journey or tools that can be used to work towards it - but that ultimate enlightenment is up to you and to us all.

text:
the national domestic violence hotline states, â€œabusive partners in lgbtq relationships use all the same tactics to gain power and control as abusive partners in heterosexual relationships â€” physical, sexual or emotional abuse, financial control, isolation and more. but abusive partners in lgbtq relationships also reinforce their tactics that maintain power and control with societal factors that compound the complexity a survivor faces in leaving or getting safe in an lgbtq relationship.â€
tactics of power & control include:
- â€œoutingâ€ a partnerâ€™s sexual orientation or gender identity. abusive partners in lgbtq relationships may threaten to â€˜outâ€™ victims to family members, employers, community members and others.
- saying that no one will help the victim because s/he is lesbian, gay, bisexual or transgender, or that for this reason, the partner â€œdeservesâ€ the abuse.
- justifying the abuse with the notion that a partner is not â€œreallyâ€ lesbian, gay, bisexual or transgender (i.e. the victim may once have had/may still have relationships, or express a gender identity, inconsistent with the abuserâ€™s definitions of these terms). this can be used both as a tool in verbal and emotional abuse as well as to further the isolation of a victim from the community.
- monopolizing support resources through an abusive partnerâ€™s manipulation of friends and family supports and generating sympathy and trust in order to cut off these resources to the victim. this is a particular issue to members of the lgbtq community where they may be fewer specific resources, neighborhoods or social outlets.
- portraying the violence as mutual and even consensual, or as an expression of masculinity or some other â€œdesirableâ€ trait.

text:
ğŸ”Š #disgusting #payattention #believewomen #empowerment washington (ap) â€” #donaldtrump lashed out friday at female protesters who have confronted senators over #supremecourt nominee brett kavanaugh, labeling them "rude elevator screamers" and "paid professionals,"
-
trump's tweet friday came before a crucial senate vote on kavanaugh, who stands accused of a high school-era sexual assault. amid a national reckoning around gender roles and sexual consent, protesters have flooded the capitol in recent days, with many women angrily addressing senators, some identifying themselves as sexual assault victims.
-
trump struck a more upbeat note after the senate pushed kavanaugh past a key procedural hurdle, saying on twitter that he was "very proud."
-
as the kavanaugh nomination has dragged out, protests â€” and direct lobbying â€” have grown.
-
an emotional exchange last week between republican sen. jeff flake and two women quickly went viral and appeared to contribute to flake's demand that a vote be delayed by a week for an fbi background investigation. on thursday several women approached republican sen. orrin hatch of utah near capitol elevators to ask why he was backing kavanaugh.
-
taking on the protesters directly, trump said in friday's tweet: "don't fall for it!"
-
after initially saying that kavanaugh's accuser, christine blasey ford, should be heard and speaking cautiously, trump has grown increasingly frustrated. placing himself firmly against the #metoo moment, he has warned that this process could lead to false accusations against men and mocked ford's emotional testimony.
-
#trump has vigorously defended kavanaugh, who denies the allegations against him. at a rally thursday night, trump mocked former sen. al franken, a minnesota democrat, for quickly vacating his seat in january in response to a string of sexual misconduct allegations and amid tremendous pressure from democrats. trump marveled at the speed, saying "boy, did he fold up like a wet rag."
â€”

text:
today were gifted with a third gender, and focusing on perpetuating the problematic and  disingenuous myth of white fragility is getting us nowhere -- this is not a war on sex, it's a war on the social construction of gender policts that has bound all of us to world's of performance, not our base humanity
.

and, frankly, i like an old school man. i feel comforted by it, but i'm old, stale and the world my conscience has made sense of has proved threatening to our kids. we need to build a better world ...now that the new majority is brown, which is code for sane
.

and white girls involved in the #metoo movement should be ashamed of themselves for including stories of "regretful", *consensual* sex among cases of rape and molestation.... if this is serious? get the government involved, set a plan and work towards policy change, not just revenge on a man who pulled out his dick in the 80s. it's cheap, trashy and filled with non-stories
.

again, i was molested as a kid and like many girls suffered under the burden of sexual violence for years. it really took it's toll on my psyche in all ways -- the answer is not personal "revenge" it's a total deconstruction of social ideals of gender, and the rituals that sustain the psychology
.

get a fucking grip, white people
.

and um, not to backslide? but if you want to date me? you have to be a alpha male, like, made in the 90s or late 80s. sorry. i'm old and out of touch, but it is my preference. i just know how to "cook" for you, if you agree to take out the "trash". but, for our kids? we need to learn the language of their new world
.

and i'm *notorious* for being a "non-joiner" but here is the reason: i like an agenda. today? kids march for no reason, towards nothing. think back to the march on washington, only 50+ years ago! it was organized *with government involvement. there was a powerful feedback loop between the people and the standing presidents. now? we just get the likes of meg newman to make white girls famous, passing forth long continued history white girls love of the public hanging
.

it's sick, but moreover, it's old, stale and confused. all "revolutions" (...this is not a revolution) need order

text:
"hope is not a lottery ticket you can sit on the sofa and clutch, feeling lucky. it is an axe you break down doors with in an emergency." rebecca solnitâ£
â£
gratitude to all the women pushing through re-lived trauma to stand up for what's right. i wish you didn't have to. as men we should be holding ourselves and one another accountable. we need to be the ones speaking out. we must be the ones to teach boys that they are responsible for their actions; that they are entitled to no special privileges just because of their chromosomes; that women (and all life forms, for that matter) are inherently deserving of respect; that self-worth or "coolness" should be determined by how one treats others, not one's sexual prowess or toughness; that conquest and achievement ought never to be part of our outlook on sex; and so, so much more.â£
â£
we are all guilty of upholding and reinforcing patriarchy, especially in the seemingly innocuous ways, and it harms all of us. i for damn sure have engaged in problematic behaviors throughout my life. i expect to be actively unlearning gender bias til the day i die, and i try to carry into each day an intention to dismantle toxic masculinity -- with the boys i teach at school, with my male friends and coworkers, with everyone i interact with. i'm no expert but i think i'm getting better every day. â£
â£
badass women have been resisting and fighting to tear down the patriarchy for as long as it has existed -- it would be a lot easier to do so if we could all stop propping it up. don't just disengage with patriarchy -- betray it. tear that shit down, it's a cage. your life and the lives of those around you will be immeasurably better for it; i promise. â£
â£

text: i just have to take a minute to explain how proud i am right now! one of my best friends in the whole world is on tv right now sharing her story with america on the one year anniversary of the #metoo movement! for those of you who read her story, amber came forward and not only did the community fail her, they tried to destroy her.  this is too familiar for too many women who have. (in my case i became labeled the "whore who called rape") amber has never given up and never backed down. she remains a voice for victims. i truly admire her bravery and strength. i wish i had a even a fraction of it. i still have too much fear and guilt and shame to speak out as i'm sure many women do but amber's example gives us all strength!! thank you amber for being unapologetically exactly who you are. i love you more than you will ever ever know!!

text:
on fridays we wear black (and strike a power pose).
.
itâ€™s important to remember that the disability community is significantly more likely to experience sexual harassment and violenceâ€”and exploring how, and why, should be an important part of any related discussion.
.
the desexualization of disabled people also means that our voices are often discounted in conversations of sexual violence.
.
also, the infantilization of disabled people, treating them as exceptional because of their disability status. the popular notion that cruelty to disabled people is â€œbeyond the paleâ€ perpetuates the idea that sexual harassment and assault donâ€™t happen in the disability community, kim saunder said, because of the widespread belief that â€œwho would do such a thing?â€
.
so... today iâ€™m reminding you that this conversation, #blackfriday, needs to take note of and include those of us who are disabled and have experienced sexual assault or harassment or violence.
.
no more leaving disability out of the movement. #metoo #stopkavanaugh

text: there is this talk i give to every employee i have ever hired. it goes like this, â€œi am in the business of seduction.  seducing clients. seducing subjects.â€ (i guess even trying to seduce followers to like me here online!) i then continue, â€œif there is ever anything said or done that makes you in the least bit uncomfortable you need to tell me right away. do not hold it in. do not try to figure out the best time to tell me.  i need to know that unless i hear otherwise, you are good with all we are doing and how we are doing it.â€ now my part of that talk is never to do anything that makes anyone who works with me uncomfortable.  this is not a hard thing to do - it just requires being respectful and aware of others at all times.  most new employees look at me like i am a bit nuts.  some thank me.  never has anyone said - even once - that they were made uncomfortable by anything going on in the workplace (or outside of it involving our studio). respecting each other is something very basic to just being a good person and should not be considered some magical quality.  we just need to teach each other what that means. #metoo #respect #teachyourchildren  this picture of @maxlenderman lifting his eyeshades was shot for a #gooddaychocolate ad campaign and not shot to be politicized here...but just thought it was so perfect.

text:
i stood on the beach this morning holding the words from a friend yesterday. words that dropped me to the floor. crying into the cold tile... hoping the dog wouldn't step on my face. "you aren't damaged goods. you are wonderfully heroically vulnerably human." yes. and in that moment on my kitchen floor all i felt was broken. over the oldest of traumas and assaults. over the evil that has been done and continues to be done to humanity.

today i remembered the profound god moments that have brought me to this point. when i couldn't stand in the place i knew he was calling me to, he helped me place my toes on the line. he called me to stand fast. he called me to lock shields. he called me to kneel in the face of the biggest storms until i rose and became the storm.

this shit will not end me. quitting has never been an option. 
i am tired. it's real. it's believed.

in all of me... you are believed and heard. 
today i rest. tomorrow i rise.

#wildandholy #wildernessisholy #freerangepastor #ivegotnostringsonme #welcometothenewage #nosurrender #smashthebox #notsorry #riseup #resist #notakebacks #metoo

text:
anew presenter spotlight:

michelle higgins is director of faith for justice. she is honored to work as an organizer on campaigns for electoral justice and prison abolition, and she serves as a worship leader at south city church. saint louis is michelle's hometown. she is often speaking about and studying the intersections of womanism and covenant theology. michelle will be speaking on #metoo and masculinity in the church at the saturday morning session.

#ffjanew2018
name: Faith for Justice

text:
you are not â€œcrazyâ€ if you went back to your abuser/ rapist. you are not crazy for missing him/her. you are not crazy for fantasizing about a life in which this person does not harm you- and for repeatedly thinking you can work out and end up happy. you are not crazy for not hating them. you are not crazy for not putting them on blast or having your friends beat them up or insisting they never be around you again. you are not crazy for not filing charges, nor are you crazy if you did, nor are you crazy if you filed charges then went back with that person anyway. you are not crazy for any of the mixed emotions. your feelings are valid.
.
.
pretty much every day since this election, we have been forced to relive our most traumatic memories and prove to the world why mentally and/ or physically abusing someone matters. why we matter. why we need change. .
.
most abusive relationships involve a lot of gaslighting. it causes you to doubt everything you know to be real. you lose who you are, you believe it is your fault, and that this is what you are worth. abusers use isolation tactics and know when to show â€œloveâ€. they know when to pretend like you are in control- so that you think the decision to accept them back into your life is yours. calling someone in this situation crazy, or trying to control what they are doing causes victims to default back to their abuser, because you feel like they are the only person who wonâ€™t think you are crazy. itâ€™s comforting in a situation where you have no control and no actual support because good intentions of others often lack empathy, and we all want to feel in control of our own life. .
.
we all want to help our loved ones. imo: the best way to do it is to listen- not tell them what to do/ how you feel. most people in abusive relationships know they are in a bad place, but stay anyway because it is not bad 100% of the time. they are not dumb. they are not crazy. they know what is going on in their life far better than anyone else and they just need trust- not judgments, not questions on why they havenâ€™t left. please show love, support, and let them speak. this would have gotten me out so much earlier than i did.

text:
the past few days have been tough. 
the past few weeks have been tough. 
the past few months have been tough. 
itâ€™s tough to be reminded that women still arenâ€™t believed. itâ€™s tough to watch a women come forward about her abuse by a man who is about to be appointed to one of the most powerful political seats. itâ€™s tough to watch this man react the same way your abuser did whenever you tried to confront him about your pain. itâ€™s tough to have people mock and ridicule her. itâ€™s tough to have friends and family youâ€™ve known your entire life say things like â€œsheâ€™s just trying to ruin his lifeâ€, â€œshe doesnâ€™t have any proof so she must be lyingâ€, and â€œshe just wants attentionâ€. itâ€™s tough because those are all the things i thought about myself when trying to come to terms with my abuse. after two long years of sexual and mental abuse, it took months of therapy and internal arguments to finally believe that i had actually been abused. i was so unbelievably manipulated that i never thought to even try to maintain any physical evidence. i was so embarrassed that i never wanted to admit to another human being that something might be wrong. i was in denial for so long and hiding in fear for even longer that by the time i did report, i was too tired and too broken to think i deserved a fair shot at justice. i was told i would have maybe a 50/50 chance of being believed. thatâ€™s a chance i didnâ€™t feel like i could take. my abuser walks free and may never see any consequences for his actions.

iâ€™m disappointed, but i know the realities about whatâ€™s happening in our world right now. ignorance, fear, hatred, and bigotry are winning. as i sat in my therapists office and yelled about how angry and frustrated i was, she calmly said â€œthis anger has power, use it.â€ i will never stop fighting. i will never stop shouting about this injustice. i will never give up. not for me, but for everyone and anyone who could benefit from hearing my story and feeling my pain. 
i may never ever see justice for my own experiences, i canâ€™t control that. and thatâ€™s okay. but i can fight to ensure that the world will one day change. 
#whyididntreport #ibelievechristineblaseyford #timesup #metoo

today has been hard for feminists, women, allies, and especially survivors. but as a silver lining, powerful young women like nadia murad, an iraqi victim of sexual violence and human trafficking (who just won the nobel peace prize), have begun to speak out. the trend of victims beginning to talk is only growing. that is good news. destroying the stigma around sharing experiences with assault and r*pe is vital to changing rape culture in america and around the world. and to change this culture we have to open up and talk about things. so proud to be witnessing history, despite a disheartening close senate vote on kavanaugh.

with what has been in the media during the week or so, i feel that it is time to speak my truth. what i am about to write has taken me about 24 years to do and it still terrifies me to post.  i am a two-time survivor of a sexual assault.  i have been sexual assaulted by a family friend as a child and also date raped during a guyâ€™s attempt at a one-night stand when i was 19.  just like dr. ford, i did not report my date rape of these crimes because i was scared and afraid of the consequences that i would happen afterwards. i also completely blocked out the childhood sexual assault until it came up 3 years ago after an intense flashback and dealt with it through intense trauma therapy.  i would like to use this rare opportunity to speak up and show others who may have been a similar situation that you are not alone. i also would like to use this opportunity to move forward with my life. it has been a very challenging couple of weeks.  i wanted to speak up sooner, but did not want to do it without my support system nearby. i have been completely offended by what has been said in the media.  enough is enough! time is up! it is time to change our culture and start believing women. 
#timesup #believesurvivors #beingbrave #metoo #rapesurvivor #enoughisenough #repost @poetrybysrc with @get_repost

text:
i have not been sexually assaulted. (it used to be called rape.) i have had a lot of sex that felt like rape. i have wondered what i was doing here a lot. i have been pushed around by men.  yes, me. i have had men get violent with me. i have been around men with bad tempers. i have been with men who donâ€™t listen to me. i have been around a lot of men with bad tempers. i have been with men who ought to be ashamed of themselves.

you know who you are. 
all #women know what i mean.

when #kavanaugh is confirmed, #women will turn to terror. 
female rage has found its sweet spot. and this is a picture of me from 2008 in new haven, when i was about to graduate from #yale law school, which was such a special place that has come to stand for the worst things. it turns out you have to be vigilant. those are some #bordercollies i know, who look a lot like my dog, but not him. funny how life turns out. now even picture captions are #political. #dogsofinstagram #rescuedogs #metoo

text:
what's going on, people! welcome to another english only thursday! have you thought about how much new information you receive every week these days? have you considered how that affects you as a person? do you become smarter? better? more practical? more prepared? more angry or afraid? or more fooled? chances are, most people, if they are honest with themselves, would answer yes to all of these questions. we try to seek information that interests us, but we inevitably get exposed to all kinds of other stuff ranging from wisdom to complete junk. one change that i find myself going through is increasing doubt. not sceptical doubt, but curious doubt. when i don't dismiss, but question everything.
.

whoa, that was a lot of hard words!
.

one way to call this doubt is curiosity, our natural drive to improve our lives. there is a saying in english - curiosity killed a cat. that's what parents say to children when they explore things that they are better off not knowing about. but next thing parents know, their children are off to examine or experiment with something else. and this hunger for knowledge stays with us all our lives, at least while we are in lucid mind. when someone begins telling us about something, and then abruptly stops and says "oh, nevermind", we instantnly have a burning desire to know what they were going to say, no matter how irrelevant their story was.
.

the more information we acquire, the more curious we become. on this path we went from inventing the wheel to sending a drone to the sun (true story). but what separates bullshit from real knowledge is our ability for critical thinking. to gather and analyze evidence, to formulate falsifiable hypothesies, design experiments and to accept that we can make mistakes. being objective, though difficult, is also within human ability. and that is the kind of doubt i am talking about. when a person can doubt something she sincerely believes to be true, it is a testament of our supremacy on this planet. we are the only species that have that capacity.
.

a quote from an old russian movie:
.
- who knows more a fool or a wise man?
- a fool. wise man doubts everything.
.

text:
twice. both close friends, both at unc, both men that claimed at some point to be in love with me, both men who have thanked me repeatedly for â€˜saving their livesâ€™ and being their turning point, bringing them hope and goodness, acting as a singular point of light and grace and joy. both men have admitted what they did. one of them will be running for office soon and has approached me about whether or not i will publicly name him. â€”â€”
as a political scientist and as a social studies teacher, the kavanaugh hearing has left me completely stunned and exasperated. as a woman, i am nauseated. as a victim of sexual assault, i am just exhausted. i have cried so much in the last three weeks. i have had to avoid the department office because the men with whom i work have been discussing the situation loudly and passionately... and with no apparent vested interest beyond a fierce debate. i have comforted students, old and new. i have listened as the teenagers in my classroom have worked through feelings and misunderstandings; i have told the boys that this is not normal, that they are capable of respect and kindness and their actions matter tremendously, and the girls that they are valuable, powerful, worthy of respect and belief, and never, ever bring this on themselves. â€”â€”
it is your responsibility to speak up on my, on our, behalf too; it isnâ€™t possible for you to know just how many women in your life are silent about their own #metoo moments. you have no idea. and none of us can do this work alone - weâ€™re trying, screaming, ripping ourselves open again and again, but it just isnâ€™t working. itâ€™s going to take everyone to effect the change we need. if you arenâ€™t sure of what to do or just feel helpless, please message me. iâ€™m here to fight with and for you.
