text:
the winners of the #nobelpeaceprize for 2018 are dr denis mukwege and nadia murad. they are helping better the lives of victims of sexual violence and human trafficking. 
_

dr mukwege is a gynecologist helping victims of sexual violence in the democratic republic of congo, where he founded the panzi hospital, a @untrustfundevaw grantee. according to him, he tries to heal his patients not only physically, but also psychologically â€œin order to restore their dignity and their capacity to defend their own rights and fight stigma, the humiliation and discrimination they face in their community.â€
_

nadia murad was kidnapped in 2014 at age 19 in iraq, held hostage and constantly subjected to sexual violence. since then, she has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering.

_

text:
a week ago, i joined #cancelkavanaugh protests at the supreme court, and it's been an emotional roller coaster since. it's easy to feel discouraged, but i want to keep sharing what's happening behind the scenes of the media circus.

unless you actively pay attention, or hear about celebrities getting arrested, you might not know that hundreds of grassroots activists have shown up every. damn. day since this nomination process started.

i shared two posts earlier this week about my experience with this last friday. today i continue the story: how it ended that day, and why i'm inspired to show up more.

surrounded by police, we met up next to the giant black sculpture in the hart atrium. hundreds of people milled about in near-silence. raising your voice or sitting on the floor is prohibited unless you're willing to risk arrest.

we gathered with women who drove cross-country overnight to face their representatives. female + non-binary assault survivors. women of color. people with wheelchairs, service dogs, translators. lgbtq allies. men. mothers with children in tow.

we waited and listened as tension built. then, above us, protestors on the balconies unfurled @womensmarch banners and started chanting. the crowd erupted, fists raised in response, chanting back. in minutes, police started making arrests.

quickly, we split up and headed to key senate offices. my group flooded the office of @sensusancollins to sit in and share our stories with her staff. the room was in tears hearing how assault victims' lives have been destroyed, in part because society keeps glossing over the terrible behavior of men, putting them in charge of shit, and then wondering why the fuck things are like this.

we left her office and stood chanting in the hallway, waiting to be arrested if necessary, when we heard that the investigation would move forward. and for a moment, we felt victorious. but we need to do more.

when you think you don't have time to take action, remember the people who show up every day.

when you feel too scared to call a politician, think of those who stand up in person for you.

when you don't know what to do, do something instead of nothing.

and vote.
name: Elle VanDyne
tweet_full:
a week ago, i joined #cancelkavanaugh protests at the supreme court, and it is been an emotional roller coaster since. it is easy to feel discouraged, but i want to keep sharing what's happening behind the scenes of the media circus.

unless you actively pay attention, or hear about celebrities getting arrested, you might not know that hundreds of grassroots activists have shown up every. damn. day since this nomination process started.

i shared two posts earlier this week about my experience with this last friday. today i continue the story: how it ended that day, and why i am inspired to show up more.

surrounded by police, we met up next to the giant black sculpture in the hart atrium. hundreds of people milled about in near-silence. raising your voice or sitting on the floor is prohibited unless you are willing to risk arrest.

we gathered with women who drove cross-country overnight to face their representatives. female + non-binary assault survivors. women of color. people with wheelchairs, service dogs, translators. lgbtq allies. men. mothers with children in tow.

we waited and listened as tension built. then, above us, protestors on the balconies unfurled @womensmarch banners and started chanting. the crowd erupted, fists raised in response, chanting back. in minutes, police started making arrests.

quickly, we split up and headed to key senate offices. my group flooded the office of @sensusancollins to sit in and share our stories with her staff. the room was in tears hearing how assault victims' lives have been destroyed, in part because society keeps glossing over the terrible behavior of men, putting them in charge of shit, and then wondering why the fuck things are like this.

we left her office and stood chanting in the hallway, waiting to be arrested if necessary, when we heard that the investigation would move forward. and for a moment, we felt victorious. but we need to do more.

when you think you do not have time to take action, remember the people who show up every day.

when you feel too scared to call a politician, think of those who stand up in person for you.

when you do not know what to do, do something instead of nothing.

and vote.

text:
after a life of loss, abandonemnent, and over sheltering, i have a hard time of letting things go. 
a week from from tomorrow will mark 2 years of a great loss of my son'sÂ  first home. the place i brought him to after he was born, the memories we made there, along with a shit load of stuff that was left there because we couldn't bring it all. taken by the house cleaners that scurry everything left by folks that had their homes foreclosed on. remaining now, are the boxes that may hold memories of my old home, that lay stacked upon each other, like a tower of pent up loss. some things stick, and just have to go in order for me to have a livable space within my now small home, and within my heart and soul. although it's been quite sometime, its time!! my over sheltering comes from both keeping me from everything as a child, but also inflicting my eyes onto things a child should not see. abuse comes in all forms, and that is how it all started. it scared me. leaving me so timid, shy, and very reserved. so much of it, that i became the silent child in my family. i branched out later after a traumatic experience that left me different in my early teen years. always searching for love. and unfortunately the boys were no different to the men now. very hurtful, cheaters, and then domestic abusers later in life. i just couldn't catch a break. i can say i've grown to be a better person in my own right, by my own doing to get better, for the better, but my mind is always going back. i really wish it wouldn't. i miss so much that i could never get back, even if i tried. i feel i'm just living my life to make it, but never to make it more acceptable on my own, to myself, for myself. and without the help of others to make me feel invincible, happy, settled within, its a neverending battle. hopefully the war within me will find a brighter light at the end of the tunnel, and keep going towards it, rather than backwards. just wishing upon a star, & having lots of hope. tgif sweetğŸ’“s.
#myrawwords #mytruths #mylife
#survivorofabuse #stillawarriorchic
#metoo #hoarderish #barelyperfect

october 9, 2018

you can join us online in the chat room: blogtalkradio.com/connectthecity

reposting old poems
because my mouth is full
of old sorrow.
. . .
iâ€™ll sing a chorus of justice
if it will make you believe her.

how many do you need

to sing my song before

itâ€™s real?

i will go to all the women i know

and ask them

to put their heart in their throat

and pray we all wont choke.

in unison weâ€™ll step back

to the nights, to the days, to the

early morning where we were

too drunk, or too weak, or too
manipulated,

to be who we really are,

who we were always meant to be.

weâ€™ll re-smell the cigarette breathe,
re-see the colors of the poster on the wall,

re-hear the laughter,

remember.

kiss the nightmare again when

all we wanted was a kiss.

when all we wanted was a drink.

when all we wanted was love.

when all we wanted was to walk home.

when all we wanted was to be left alone.

when all we got was a ghost.
-

iâ€™ll bring them all

if youâ€™ll believe her.

if men fear the accusations they may face

picture what i fear for my daughter.

if i sing will you believe her one day?
-

we can hold hands in a hashtag

cry in our husbands and strangers

and friends and wifeâ€™s and coworkers

arms.

stuff ourselves into closets,

balled up in an origami folds

to make us disappear.

but donâ€™t underestimate the power

of ten thousand voices

singing softly.

when the blood runs from our mouth

from broken hearts in our throat

youâ€™ll know times up. -

have you ever heard something so sad

itâ€™s beautiful?

how many do you need to sing my song

before itâ€™s real?
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
this week in our #weeklylookback: while the new yorker profiled one supreme court judge, ruth bader ginsburg, and her unlikely path to the supreme court, the fbi investigated supreme court justice nominee, federal judge brett kavanaugh, for an incident involving alcohol in college. the #metoo movement has become such an integral part of the moment, that it has even reached the highest court in the land, the supreme court. .
.
.
the national institute of alcohol abuse and alcoholism found that 25 percent of american women have experienced sexual assault, including rape. approximately one-half of those cases involve alcohol consumption by the perpetrator, victim, or both. additionally, the national council on alcoholism and drug dependence estimated that alcohol is a factor in 40 percent of violent crimes.
.
.
.
often times baby boomers and gen x-ers can be heard thankfully musing that they did not grow up in the age of social media. as evidenced by what is going on right now with the confirmation hearings, it doesn't necessarily take social media for the past to be revisited. most students having a good time in college don't think what they do at a frat party can come up in a job interview.
.
.
.
vice media reported that students were "unsurprised" by the sexual assault allegations against kavanaugh. is this true? tell us your thoughts in the comments.

tweet_full:
this week in our #weeklylookback: while the new yorker profiled one supreme court judge, ruth bader ginsburg, and her unlikely path to the supreme court, the fbi investigated supreme court justice nominee, federal judge brett kavanaugh, for an incident involving alcohol in college. the #metoo movement has become such an integral part of the moment, that it has even reached the highest court in the land, the supreme court. .
.
.
the national institute of alcohol abuse and alcoholism found that 25 percent of american women have experienced sexual assault, including rape. approximately one-half of those cases involve alcohol consumption by the perpetrator, victim, or both. additionally, the national council on alcoholism and drug dependence estimated that alcohol is a factor in 40 percent of violent crimes.
.
.
.
often times baby boomers and gen x-ers can be heard thankfully musing that they did not grow up in the age of social media. as evidenced by what is going on right now with the confirmation hearings, it does not necessarily take social media for the past to be revisited. most students having a good time in college do not think what they do at a frat party can come up in a job interview.
.
.

text: â€œi am fighting for justice for all missing and murdered indigenous women. this is their #metoo. a vote for kavanaugh, is a vote against women. we need to stand together and support each other. and take down the patriarchy!â€ yesterday, last night, hell, the last couple weeks has been motivating, heartbreaking, devastating, but empowering.... to see so many brave women, survivors and allies step up to #stopkavanaugh. iâ€™m a survivor of two different violations on my body. being with everyone, made me feel safe. i was honored to share space with survivors last night on tongva lands to shine light on not only stopping this vote, but on our missing and murdered indigenous women and the violenence against women act. vawa has a deadline to be re-authorized on september 30. congress, well, the senators who are voting for kavanaugh (some), have voted against vawa in the past, yet they say they care about women and our rights. seems odd. but they are now using it as budget leverage, yes, they are using vawa as leverage in the stop gap spending bill in december. until vawa, tribes couldnâ€™t prosecute on their own lands. a loop hole in the colonial system that lets offenders get away with murder, rape, domestic violence and more. itâ€™s incredibly crucial to vote in these mid-terms. get to the polls. stand together, love one another, support each other, and letâ€™s continue to use our voices! a huge congratulations to iraqi human rights activist nadia murad, who very deservingly won today the 2018 nobel peace prize. 
after being kidnapped, tortured, and used as a sex slave by isis, who killed 600 of her villagers, murad is using her voice to end use of sexual violence as a weapon of war and armed conflict. 
murad is a un goodwill ambassador and has been working through her organization â€œnadiaâ€™s initiativeâ€ to help free captured yazidi women and others who are desperate to be freed from the horrific sex slave trade.
she is the first iraqi to win the nobel prize.
